      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA software (Ansys Mechanical 2023 R1) operates under a documented SQA plan with version control, regression testing, and change management procedures consistent with ASME V&V 40 Gradation 2.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2023 R1 is used under an enterprise SQA framework with documented installation qualification, version-controlled input files stored in a validated PLM repository, and a regression test suite executed at each software update. SQA records are archived and traceable to the simulation runs supporting this COU."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems representative of the physics (large-deformation elastoplastic contact) are solved and compared against published analytical or reference solutions; agreement within 2%.",
      "rationale": "Three NAFEMS benchmark problems covering nonlinear contact and elastoplastic beam bending were solved using the project solver configuration. All results agreed with reference solutions within 1.4%, satisfying the Gradation 2 code-verification criterion."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "A mesh convergence study demonstrates that QoI changes by less than 2% between the penultimate and final refinement levels; Richardson extrapolation used to estimate discretization uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "A four-level mesh convergence study was performed on the screw-rod construct model. Stiffness QoI changed by 1.1% between the two finest meshes; Richardson extrapolation yielded a discretization uncertainty of 0.8%. The production mesh (approximately 420,000 elements, second-order tetrahedral) was selected as the converged configuration."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Residual force and displacement convergence tolerances are documented; iterative solver residuals remain below 1e-4 for all load steps.",
      "rationale": "Newton-Raphson iteration was used with force residual tolerance 1e-5 and displacement residual tolerance 1e-4. All 47 load increments across the 11 virtual specimens converged within 8 iterations. No unconverged steps were accepted."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "A documented simulation workflow with peer review and independent input-deck check is in place; at least one independent reviewer verifies boundary conditions and material assignments.",
      "rationale": "The simulation workflow was executed by a senior FEA engineer and independently reviewed by a second engineer who verified boundary condition definitions, material property assignments, and contact pair specifications against the V&V plan. Review sign-off is recorded in the PLM system."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The constitutive model (bilinear isotropic hardening for Ti-6Al-4V rod, linear elastic for UHMWPE block) is justified by literature data and sensitivity analysis demonstrating that alternative model forms change QoIs by less than 5%.",
      "rationale": "Bilinear isotropic hardening parameters for Ti-6Al-4V were derived from three independent literature sources; a Chaboche kinematic hardening model was evaluated as an alternative and changed predicted yield force by 3.2%, within the 5% threshold. The chosen model form is judged adequate for monotonic loading to 40 mm displacement."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties and geometric parameters are sourced from traceable measurements or certified material certificates; uncertainty in inputs is propagated through a one-at-a-time sensitivity study.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V rod elastic modulus and yield strength were taken from material certificates for the production lot. UHMWPE block modulus was measured by the testing laboratories (mean 0.94 GPa, CV 4.2%). Screw geometry was obtained from CAD files verified against CMM measurements. A one-at-a-time sensitivity study showed that input uncertainty contributes 1.8% to QoI uncertainty, within acceptable bounds."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "At least 10 physical specimens from at least one production lot are tested; specimen dimensions are verified against nominal CAD geometry within manufacturing tolerances.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs from two production lots were tested. Specimen dimensions were verified by the testing laboratories against the device drawing; all dimensions were within specified tolerances. The sample size of N=11 across two lots provides adequate representation of production variability for a Gradation 3 assessment."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Testing is conducted at a minimum of two load levels or two fixture configurations representative of the clinical use envelope; environmental conditions (temperature, humidity) are recorded.",
      "rationale": "Testing was performed at a single load configuration (ASTM F1717 standard fixture, room temperature 23 ± 2°C). While environmental conditions were recorded and are consistent with the FEA boundary conditions, only one test condition was evaluated. This limits the factor achievement to Gradation 2, one level below the required Gradation 3. This gap is noted in the overall credibility assessment and accepted given that the single condition is the regulatory standard configuration."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA boundary conditions (fixture geometry, load application point, support conditions) are demonstrated to be equivalent to experimental conditions within documented tolerances.",
      "rationale": "Fixture geometry in the FEA model was constructed from laboratory fixture drawings verified against as-built CMM measurements. Load application point and angular offset were matched to ASTM F1717 specifications. A sensitivity study on fixture compliance showed less than 0.5% effect on stiffness QoI, confirming equivalency of input parameters."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoI differences are quantified using a normalized validation metric (E/uval) accounting for both simulation and experimental uncertainty; E/uval < 1.96 for all QoIs.",
      "rationale": "E/uval was computed for stiffness (1.12), yield force (1.43), and force at 40 mm (0.98). All values fall below the 1.96 threshold. Experimental uncertainty was estimated from the N=11 sample standard deviation; simulation uncertainty combined discretization, input, and numerical solver contributions via RSS. The output comparison satisfies the Gradation 3 criterion."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The QoIs predicted by FEA (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) are directly linked to the regulatory submission claims and to the failure modes of clinical concern (fatigue initiation, permanent deformation).",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness governs load transfer to adjacent spinal levels; yield force and force at 40 mm displacement are direct indicators of permanent deformation risk under intraoperative and postoperative loading. All three QoIs appear explicitly in the 510(k) substantial equivalence claims and are the quantities specified in ASTM F1717. Relevance is fully established."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The validation scenario (ASTM F1717 compression-bending, non-cannulated 7.5 mm screw, UHMWPE block) is representative of the COU geometry, loading mode, and material system.",
      "rationale": "The validation specimens are identical in geometry, material, and surface finish to the device described in the COU. The ASTM F1717 compression-bending loading mode directly represents the dominant clinical loading scenario. Testing across two independent laboratories confirms that results are not laboratory-specific. The validation activities are judged highly relevant to the COU."
    }
